    <section id="warnings">
      <h2>Warnings</h2>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title="Warning: Excellence in One Domain Can Crowd Out Others">
        The pursuit of mastery in a single domain, if pursued without reflection, can consume resources — time, attention, energy — that other important domains desperately need. Many who achieved professional excellence paid enormous costs in relationships, health, or personal development. Excellence is a philosophy for all domains of a well-lived life, not a license to sacrifice everything else for one.
      </ContentBox>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title="Warning: High Standards Can Become Contempt for Others">
        People who develop genuinely high standards in their domain sometimes fall into the trap of contempt for those who have not. This is both philosophically wrong (Aristotle's excellence includes the virtue of justice, which requires fair treatment of others) and practically self-defeating (contempt destroys the relationships and mentorship dynamics that excellence depends on). Hold high standards for yourself; extend generosity to others.
      </ContentBox>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title="Warning: Excellence Without Joy Is Unsustainable">
        Aristotle insisted that the excellent person takes pleasure in excellent activity. If your pursuit of excellence has become joyless — if you are grinding without genuine engagement, performing without inner investment — something has gone wrong. Sustainable excellence requires that you genuinely care about the work. If that caring has eroded, investigating why is more important than pushing harder.
      </ContentBox>
    </section>

